1
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:15,675
Oh, for a muse of fire...

2
00:02:15,775 --> 00:02:20,893
that would ascend the
brightest heaven of invention.

3
00:02:41,548 --> 00:02:44,450
A kingdom for a stage,

4
00:02:44,653 --> 00:02:46,147
princes to act...

5
00:02:46,766 --> 00:02:51,173
and monarchs to behold
the swelling scene.

6
00:02:51,889 --> 00:02:54,542
Then should the warlike harry,
like himself,

7
00:02:54,642 --> 00:02:56,400
assume the port of Mars...

8
00:02:56,500 --> 00:02:59,922
and at his heels,
leashed in like hounds,

9
00:03:00,022 --> 00:03:04,852
should famine, sword and fire
crouch for employment.

10
00:03:04,952 --> 00:03:08,342
But pardon, gentles all,

11
00:03:08,442 --> 00:03:10,870
the flat, unraised spirits...

12
00:03:10,970 --> 00:03:13,655
that have dared
on this unworthy scaffold...

13
00:03:13,755 --> 00:03:17,649
to bring forth
so great an object.

14
00:03:17,916 --> 00:03:21,595
Can this cockpit hold
the vasty fields of France

15
00:03:21,695 --> 00:03:25,245
or may we cram
within this wooden "o"...

16
00:03:25,345 --> 00:03:29,790
the very casques that did affright
the air at Agincourt?

17
00:03:29,890 --> 00:03:31,350
Oh, pardon.

18
00:03:32,322 --> 00:03:34,400
Let us, ciphers
to this great account,

19
00:03:34,500 --> 00:03:37,058
on your imaginary forces work.

20
00:03:37,158 --> 00:03:39,651
For it is your thoughts
that now must deck our kings,

21
00:03:39,751 --> 00:03:43,013
carry them here, there,
jumping o'er times,

22
00:03:43,113 --> 00:03:47,655
turning the accomplishment of
many years into an hourglass.

23
00:03:47,755 --> 00:03:52,649
For the which supply,
admit me, chorus, to this history,

24
00:03:52,749 --> 00:03:55,618
who, prologue-like,

25
00:03:55,917 --> 00:03:58,412
your humble patience pray...

26
00:03:58,512 --> 00:04:00,933
gently to hear,

27
00:04:01,617 --> 00:04:03,657
kindly to judge...

28
00:04:04,113 --> 00:04:06,023
our play!

29
00:04:15,574 --> 00:04:18,126
My lord, I'll tell you.

30
00:04:23,450 --> 00:04:26,361
That self bill is urged,
which, in the 11th year...

31
00:04:26,461 --> 00:04:29,114
of the last king's reign was
like to have passed against us.

32
00:04:29,214 --> 00:04:32,123
But how, my lord,
shall we resist it now?

33
00:04:32,223 --> 00:04:33,692
It must be thought on.

34
00:04:33,792 --> 00:04:36,574
If it pass against us, we lose the
better half of our possession.

35
00:04:36,674 --> 00:04:38,266
But what prevention?

36
00:04:38,754 --> 00:04:41,376
The king is full of grace
and fair regard.

37
00:04:41,476 --> 00:04:44,000
And a true lover
of the holy church.

38
00:04:44,100 --> 00:04:46,241
The courses of his youth
promised it not.

39
00:04:46,341 --> 00:04:48,193
Since his addiction
was to courses vain,

40
00:04:48,293 --> 00:04:51,652
his hours filled up
with riots, banquets,

41
00:04:51,752 --> 00:04:55,173
sports and never noted
in him any study.

42
00:04:55,273 --> 00:04:57,862
But, my good lord,
how now for the mitigation...

43
00:04:57,962 --> 00:05:00,104
Of this bill
urged by the commons?

44
00:05:00,204 --> 00:05:02,440
Doth his majesty incline
to it or no?

45
00:05:02,540 --> 00:05:05,706
He seems...
indifferent,

46
00:05:05,806 --> 00:05:09,676
or rather swaying more
upon our part.

47
00:05:09,776 --> 00:05:12,749
For I have made an offer
to his majesty,

48
00:05:12,849 --> 00:05:15,215
as touching France.

49
00:06:11,146 --> 00:06:14,112
Where is my gracious
lord of Canterbury?

50
00:06:29,939 --> 00:06:35,314
God and his angels guard your sacred
throne and make you long become it.

51
00:06:35,414 --> 00:06:36,657
Sure we thank you.

52
00:06:37,014 --> 00:06:39,188
My learned lord,
we pray you to proceed...

53
00:06:39,288 --> 00:06:42,037
and justly and religiously unfold...

54
00:06:42,137 --> 00:06:44,951
why the law salique
that they have in France,

55
00:06:45,051 --> 00:06:49,113
or should or should not
bar us in our claim.

56
00:06:49,213 --> 00:06:53,787
And pray, take heed
how you impawn our person,

57
00:06:53,887 --> 00:06:58,044
how you awake
our sleeping sword of war.

58
00:06:58,144 --> 00:07:01,439
We charge you,
in the name of God, take heed.

59
00:07:01,539 --> 00:07:06,939
For never two such kingdoms did
contend without much fall of blood.

60
00:07:09,285 --> 00:07:12,068
Then hear me,
gracious sovereign.

61
00:07:12,168 --> 00:07:16,837
There is no bar to make against
your highness' claim to France...

62
00:07:16,937 --> 00:07:21,060
but this, which they
produce from Pharamond.

63
00:07:22,602 --> 00:07:26,313
"In terram salicam
mulieres ne succedant."

64
00:07:26,413 --> 00:07:32,205
"No woman shall succeed
in Salique land."

65
00:07:32,305 --> 00:07:36,462
Which Salique land
the French unjustly gloze...

66
00:07:36,562 --> 00:07:38,351
to be the realm of France.

67
00:07:38,451 --> 00:07:42,032
Yet their own authors
faithfully affirm...

68
00:07:42,132 --> 00:07:44,722
that the land Salique
lies in Germany...

69
00:07:44,822 --> 00:07:48,308
between the floods
of Sala and of Elbe.

70
00:07:48,408 --> 00:07:51,381
Then doth it well appear
the Salique law...

71
00:07:51,481 --> 00:07:54,935
was not devised
for the realm of France,

72
00:07:55,035 --> 00:07:57,432
nor did the French possess
the Salique land...

73
00:07:57,532 --> 00:08:02,618
until 421 years after
defunction of king Pharamond,

74
00:08:02,718 --> 00:08:07,702
idly supposed
the founder of this law.

75
00:08:08,896 --> 00:08:12,670
King Pepin,
which deposed childeric,

76
00:08:12,770 --> 00:08:16,192
did, as heir general,
being descended of blithild,

77
00:08:16,292 --> 00:08:18,273
which was the daughter
to king Clothair,

78
00:08:18,373 --> 00:08:20,418
make claim and title
to the crown of France.

79
00:08:20,518 --> 00:08:24,644
Hugh Capet, also, who usurped the
crown of Charles, the duke of Lorraine,

80
00:08:24,744 --> 00:08:28,133
sole heir male of the true line
and stock of Charles the great,

81
00:08:28,233 --> 00:08:30,970
could not keep quiet in his conscience
wearing the crown of France...

82
00:08:31,070 --> 00:08:34,344
until satisfied that fair queen
Isabel, his grandmother,

83
00:08:34,444 --> 00:08:37,289
was lineal
of the Lady Ermengare,

84
00:08:37,389 --> 00:08:40,747
daughter to Charles,
the aforesaid duke of Lorraine,

85
00:08:40,847 --> 00:08:43,148
by the which marriage the line
of Charles the great...

86
00:08:43,248 --> 00:08:47,622
was reunited
to the crown of France.

87
00:08:51,507 --> 00:08:54,963
So it is clear
as is the summer sun.

88
00:08:56,789 --> 00:09:01,492
All appear to hold in right
and title of the female.

89
00:09:01,592 --> 00:09:04,790
So do the kings of France...

90
00:09:04,890 --> 00:09:07,061
unto this day.

91
00:09:10,107 --> 00:09:14,490
Howbeit, they would hold up
this salique law...

92
00:09:14,590 --> 00:09:20,219
to bar your highness
claiming from the female.

93
00:09:20,704 --> 00:09:25,312
May I, with right
and conscience,

94
00:09:25,412 --> 00:09:27,648
make this claim?

95
00:09:30,437 --> 00:09:34,048
The sin upon my head,
dread sovereign.

96
00:09:38,536 --> 00:09:41,735
Stand for your own.
Unwind your bloody flag.

97
00:09:41,835 --> 00:09:43,698
Your brother kings
and monarchs of the earth...

98
00:09:43,798 --> 00:09:45,894
do all expect that you
should rouse yourself...

99
00:09:45,994 --> 00:09:49,222
as did the former lions
of your blood.

100
00:09:49,322 --> 00:09:52,710
Never king of England had nobles
richer and more loyal subjects...

101
00:09:52,810 --> 00:09:54,862
whose hearts have left
their bodies here in England...

102
00:09:54,962 --> 00:09:56,933
and lie pavilioned
in the fields of France.

103
00:09:57,033 --> 00:09:59,301
Oh, let their bodies follow,
my dear liege,

104
00:09:59,401 --> 00:10:03,557
with blood and sword and fire
to win your right.

105
00:10:03,657 --> 00:10:05,794
In aid whereof,

106
00:10:06,184 --> 00:10:10,918
we of the spirituality
will raise your highness...

107
00:10:11,018 --> 00:10:13,701
such a mighty sum
as never did the clergy...

108
00:10:13,801 --> 00:10:17,508
at one time bring in to
any of your ancestors.

109
00:10:21,128 --> 00:10:24,355
Call in the messengers
sent from the Dauphin.

110
00:10:28,904 --> 00:10:32,645
Now are we well resolved,
and by God's help and yours,

111
00:10:32,745 --> 00:10:37,348
the noble sinews of our power,
France being ours,

112
00:10:37,448 --> 00:10:40,314
we'll bend it to our all...

113
00:10:43,559 --> 00:10:46,492
or break it all to pieces.

114
00:10:55,943 --> 00:11:00,483
Now are we well prepared to know the
pleasure of our fair cousin Dauphin.

115
00:11:00,583 --> 00:11:04,035
Your highness, lately sending into France
did claim some certain dukedoms...

116
00:11:04,135 --> 00:11:06,292
in the right of your great
predecessor, king Edward III.

117
00:11:06,392 --> 00:11:09,731
In answer of which claim,
the prince, my master,

118
00:11:09,831 --> 00:11:12,227
says that you savor
too much of your youth.

119
00:11:12,327 --> 00:11:17,986
He therefore sends you, meeter for
your spirit, this tun of treasure.

120
00:11:19,846 --> 00:11:21,853
And in lieu of this, desires
you let those dukedoms...

121
00:11:21,953 --> 00:11:23,683
that you claim
hear no more of you.

122
00:11:23,783 --> 00:11:27,074
This the Dauphin speaks.

123
00:11:27,366 --> 00:11:32,601
What... treasure, uncle?

124
00:11:38,629 --> 00:11:41,726
Tennis balls, my liege.

125
00:11:48,901 --> 00:11:52,641
We are glad the Dauphin
is so pleasant with us.

126
00:11:53,478 --> 00:11:58,178
His present and your pains
we thank you for.

127
00:11:58,757 --> 00:12:02,498
When we have matched
our rackets to these balls,

128
00:12:02,598 --> 00:12:05,507
we will in France,
by God's grace,

129
00:12:05,607 --> 00:12:10,562
play a set shall strike his
father's crown into the hazard.

130
00:12:10,662 --> 00:12:12,770
And we understand him well,

131
00:12:12,870 --> 00:12:15,361
how he comes o'er us
with our wilder days,

132
00:12:15,461 --> 00:12:17,857
not measuring what use
we made of them.

133
00:12:17,957 --> 00:12:22,370
But tell the Dauphin
I will keep my state,

134
00:12:22,470 --> 00:12:25,792
be like a king and show
my sail of greatness...

135
00:12:25,892 --> 00:12:29,185
when I do rouse me
in my throne of France.

136
00:12:29,285 --> 00:12:32,704
And tell the pleasant prince
this mock of his...

137
00:12:32,804 --> 00:12:34,593
hath turned his balls
to gunstones,

138
00:12:34,693 --> 00:12:37,312
and his soul
shall stand sore charged...

139
00:12:37,412 --> 00:12:39,649
for the wasteful vengeance
that shall fly with them.

140
00:12:39,749 --> 00:12:42,656
For many a thousand widows
shall this his mock,

141
00:12:42,756 --> 00:12:44,544
mock out of
their dear husbands,

142
00:12:44,644 --> 00:12:47,937
mock mothers from their sons,
mock castles down.

143
00:12:48,037 --> 00:12:50,304
And some are yet ungotten
and unborn...

144
00:12:50,404 --> 00:12:53,817
that shall have cause
to curse the Dauphin's scorn.

145
00:12:55,139 --> 00:12:56,768
So get you hence in peace,

146
00:12:56,868 --> 00:12:59,584
and tell the Dauphin...

147
00:12:59,684 --> 00:13:04,736
his jest... will savor
but of shallow wit...

148
00:13:04,836 --> 00:13:09,754
when thousands weep
more than did laugh at it.

149
00:13:12,067 --> 00:13:14,716
Convey them with safe conduct.

150
00:13:16,451 --> 00:13:18,043
Fare you well.

151
00:13:31,457 --> 00:13:35,350
This was a merry message.

152
00:13:35,649 --> 00:13:39,029
We hope to make the sender
blush at it.

153
00:13:40,130 --> 00:13:43,550
Therefore, my lords,
omit no happy hour...

154
00:13:43,650 --> 00:13:45,662
that may give furtherance
to our expedition.

155
00:13:45,762 --> 00:13:48,767
For we have now no thought
in us but France,

156
00:13:48,867 --> 00:13:52,890
save those to God
that run before our business.

157
00:13:52,993 --> 00:13:55,518
Therefore, let every man
now task his thought...

158
00:13:55,618 --> 00:14:00,950
that this fair action
may on foot be brought.

159
00:14:09,665 --> 00:14:12,733
Now all the youth of
England are on fire...

160
00:14:12,833 --> 00:14:16,477
and silken dalliance
in the wardrobe lies.

161
00:14:16,577 --> 00:14:20,094
For now sits expectation
in the air...

162
00:14:20,194 --> 00:14:23,613
and hides a sword,
from hilts unto the point,

163
00:14:23,713 --> 00:14:27,774
with crowns imperial,
crowns and coronets...

164
00:14:27,874 --> 00:14:32,344
promised to Harry and his followers.

165
00:14:46,655 --> 00:14:48,893
Well met, Corporal Nym.

166
00:14:48,993 --> 00:14:52,088
Good morrow,
Lieutenant Bardolph.

167
00:14:57,919 --> 00:15:01,885
What, are you and Ancient Pistol friends yet?

168
00:15:01,985 --> 00:15:05,397
For my part, I care not.

169
00:15:05,631 --> 00:15:07,091
I say little,

170
00:15:07,550 --> 00:15:12,763
but when time shall serve,
there shall be smiles.

171
00:15:14,590 --> 00:15:16,380
But that shall be as it may.

172
00:15:16,480 --> 00:15:20,124
Come, I will bestow a breakfast
to make you friends,

173
00:15:20,224 --> 00:15:23,004
and we'll be all three
sworn brothers to France.

174
00:15:23,104 --> 00:15:26,646
- Let it be so, good corporal.
- I will do as I may.

175
00:15:27,326 --> 00:15:31,388
It is certain, corporal, that Ancient
Pistol is married to Nell quickly.

176
00:15:31,488 --> 00:15:35,740
For certainly she did you wrong,
for you were betrothed to her.

177
00:15:42,686 --> 00:15:45,180
How now,
mine host Pistol?

178
00:15:45,280 --> 00:15:46,870
Base tyke!

179
00:15:47,902 --> 00:15:49,884
Callest thou me host?

180
00:15:49,984 --> 00:15:52,795
Now, by this hand,
I swear I scorn the term!

181
00:15:52,895 --> 00:15:56,059
Nor shall my Nell
keep lodgers!

182
00:15:56,159 --> 00:15:57,690
No, by my troth,
not long.

183
00:15:57,790 --> 00:16:01,337
For we can't lodge or board
a dozen or 14 gentlewomen...

184
00:16:01,437 --> 00:16:03,737
who live honestly
by the prick of their needles,

185
00:16:03,837 --> 00:16:06,617
but it shall be thought
we keep a bawdy house straight.

186
00:16:06,717 --> 00:16:10,329
- Pish!
- Pish for thee, Iceland dog!

187
00:16:10,429 --> 00:16:12,696
Good Corporal Nym,

188
00:16:13,436 --> 00:16:15,833
show thy valor
and put up thy sword.

189
00:16:15,933 --> 00:16:18,105
Will you shog off?

190
00:16:18,205 --> 00:16:22,297
Pistol, I will prick your guts
a little in good terms, as I may.

191
00:16:22,397 --> 00:16:24,442
That's the humor of it.

192
00:16:24,542 --> 00:16:27,641
- Braggart vile!
- Ah, hear me when I say,

193
00:16:27,741 --> 00:16:29,657
he that strikes
the first stroke,

194
00:16:29,757 --> 00:16:31,770
I'll run him up to the hilts,
as I'm a soldier.

195
00:16:31,870 --> 00:16:34,138
An oath of mickle might,

196
00:16:34,238 --> 00:16:38,265
and fury shall abate.

197
00:16:38,365 --> 00:16:39,365
My host Pistol!

198
00:16:39,772 --> 00:16:41,785
You must come to my master,
and you, hostess!

199
00:16:41,885 --> 00:16:44,697
He's very sick
and would to bed.

200
00:16:45,084 --> 00:16:48,274
Good Bardolph, put thy face between his
sheets and do the office of a warming pan.

201
00:16:48,374 --> 00:16:51,185
Away, you rogue.

202
00:16:51,356 --> 00:16:54,802
Faith, he's very ill.

203
00:16:57,691 --> 00:16:58,835
By my troth,

204
00:16:59,227 --> 00:17:02,422
the king has killed his heart.

205
00:17:02,588 --> 00:17:04,756
Good husband,
come home presently.

206
00:17:17,370 --> 00:17:21,015
Come, shall I make you two friends?
We must to France together.

207
00:17:21,115 --> 00:17:24,695
Why the devil should we keep
nives to cut one another's throats?

208
00:17:24,795 --> 00:17:28,695
You'll pay me the eight shillings
I won of you at betting?

209
00:17:28,795 --> 00:17:32,535
Base is the slave that pays.

210
00:17:32,635 --> 00:17:35,095
By this sword,
he that makes the first thrust,

211
00:17:35,195 --> 00:17:37,908
I'll kill him,
by this sword, I will.

212
00:17:38,394 --> 00:17:40,695
If ever you come of women,
come in quickly to Sir John.

213
00:17:40,795 --> 00:17:44,791
He is so shaked with
a burning quotidian fever...

214
00:17:44,891 --> 00:17:48,215
that it is most lamentable
to behold.

215
00:17:48,889 --> 00:17:51,254
Sweet men, come to him.

216
00:17:52,858 --> 00:17:55,287
Poor Sir John.

217
00:17:55,387 --> 00:17:58,733
A good portly man of faith.

218
00:18:04,634 --> 00:18:07,255
Aye, to a cheerful look,
a pleasing eye...

219
00:18:07,355 --> 00:18:10,995
and a most noble carriage.

220
00:18:18,233 --> 00:18:21,014
But do I not dwindle?

221
00:18:21,114 --> 00:18:24,853
My skin hangs about me
like an old lady's loose gown.

222
00:18:27,737 --> 00:18:30,904
Company, villainous company
have been the spoil of me.

223
00:18:35,001 --> 00:18:36,756
Whoo!
Hey! Hey!

224
00:18:38,904 --> 00:18:42,033
I was as virtuous
as a gentleman need to be.

225
00:18:42,135 --> 00:18:45,526
Virtuous enough.
Swore a little.

226
00:18:48,151 --> 00:18:51,476
Diced not above
seven days a week.

227
00:18:53,079 --> 00:18:55,956
Went to a bawdy house
not above once in the quarter.

228
00:18:56,056 --> 00:18:58,988
Oh!

229
00:19:00,599 --> 00:19:03,476
Paid money that I borrowed,

230
00:19:03,576 --> 00:19:05,330
three or four times.

231
00:19:07,159 --> 00:19:09,813
Lived well
and in good compass.

232
00:19:09,913 --> 00:19:12,852
What? You were so fat,
Sir John,

233
00:19:12,952 --> 00:19:17,324
that you must indeed
be out of all compass.

234
00:19:17,463 --> 00:19:20,119
Do thou amend thy face,
and I'll amend my life.

235
00:19:35,703 --> 00:19:39,577
If sack and sugar be a fault,
then God help the wicked.

236
00:19:39,677 --> 00:19:43,035
Mmm? If to be old
and merry is a sin,

237
00:19:43,135 --> 00:19:46,271
if to be fat
is to be hated,

238
00:19:46,371 --> 00:19:52,003
then no, my good lord,
when thou art king,

239
00:19:53,738 --> 00:19:57,961
banish Pistol, banish Bardolph,
banish Nym.

240
00:19:59,632 --> 00:20:01,967
But sweet Jack Falstaff,

241
00:20:02,067 --> 00:20:04,242
Aliant Jack Falstaff,

242
00:20:04,342 --> 00:20:07,574
and therefore more valiant
being as he is,

243
00:20:07,674 --> 00:20:10,130
old Jack Falstaff,

244
00:20:10,428 --> 00:20:13,948
banish not him
thy Harry's company.

245
00:20:14,048 --> 00:20:18,785
Banish plump Jack,
and banish all the world.

246
00:20:21,447 --> 00:20:25,409
I do. I will.

247
00:20:29,296 --> 00:20:34,220
but we have heard the
chimes at midnight, master Harry.

248
00:20:37,144 --> 00:20:38,968
Jesus.

249
00:20:40,060 --> 00:20:43,892
The days that we have seen.

250
00:20:45,217 --> 00:20:49,343
I know thee not, old man.

251
00:21:09,883 --> 00:21:13,178
The king hath run
bad humors on the knight.

252
00:21:14,624 --> 00:21:16,993
Nym, thou hast
spoke the right.

253
00:21:17,093 --> 00:21:22,310
His heart is fracted
and... corroborate.

254
00:21:23,818 --> 00:21:25,738
The king's a good king,

255
00:21:25,838 --> 00:21:29,002
but it must be as it may.

256
00:21:29,392 --> 00:21:32,393
He passes some humors
and careers.

257
00:21:33,044 --> 00:21:34,963
Let us condole the knight,

258
00:21:35,063 --> 00:21:40,434
for, lambkins,
we will live.

259
00:21:49,317 --> 00:21:52,167
The French, advised
by good intelligence...

260
00:21:52,267 --> 00:21:54,345
of this most dreadful
preparation,

261
00:21:54,445 --> 00:21:56,171
shake in their fear...

262
00:21:56,271 --> 00:21:59,950
and with pale policy seek
to divert the English purposes.

263
00:22:00,050 --> 00:22:05,770
Oh, England, model
to thy inward greatness.

264
00:22:05,880 --> 00:22:07,831
Like a little body
with a mighty heart.

265
00:22:07,931 --> 00:22:10,683
What mightst thou do
that honor would thee do...

266
00:22:10,783 --> 00:22:13,596
were all thy children
kind and natural?

267
00:22:13,696 --> 00:22:18,209
But see, thy fault France
hath in thee found out.

268
00:22:18,309 --> 00:22:22,183
A nest of hollow bosoms which he
fills with treacherous crowns...

269
00:22:22,283 --> 00:22:24,905
and three corrupted men.

270
00:22:25,005 --> 00:22:26,667
One, Richard Earl of Cambridge,

271
00:22:26,767 --> 00:22:29,326
and the second,
Henry Lord Scroop of Masham,

272
00:22:29,426 --> 00:22:32,721
and the third, Sir Thomas Grey, knight,
of Northumberland,

273
00:22:32,821 --> 00:22:35,829
have for the gilt of France...
oh, guilt indeed...

274
00:22:35,929 --> 00:22:38,873
confirmed conspiracy
with fearful France,

275
00:22:38,973 --> 00:22:43,197
and by their hands
this grace of kings must die,

276
00:22:43,297 --> 00:22:45,056
ere he take ship for France.

277
00:22:45,156 --> 00:22:46,722
The traitors are agreed.

278
00:22:46,822 --> 00:22:49,059
The king is set from London,

279
00:22:49,159 --> 00:22:52,391
and the scene
is now transported, gentles,

280
00:22:52,491 --> 00:22:54,434
to Southhampton.

281
00:23:06,425 --> 00:23:09,658
Before God, his grace is bold
to trust these traitors.

282
00:23:09,758 --> 00:23:11,548
They shall be apprehended
by and by.

283
00:23:11,648 --> 00:23:14,079
How smooth and even
they do bear themselves,

284
00:23:14,179 --> 00:23:18,115
as if allegiance in their bosoms sat
crowned with faith and constant loyalty.

285
00:23:18,215 --> 00:23:22,312
The king hath note of all they intend by
interception which they dream not of.

286
00:23:22,412 --> 00:23:24,361
Nay, but the man
that was his bedfellow,

287
00:23:24,461 --> 00:23:27,020
whom he hath dulled and cloyed
with gracious favors...

288
00:23:27,120 --> 00:23:30,127
That he should,
for a foreign purse,

289
00:23:30,227 --> 00:23:35,083
so sell his sovereign's life
to death and treachery.

290
00:23:41,278 --> 00:23:44,694
Now sits the wind fair,
and we will aboard.

291
00:23:50,952 --> 00:23:53,352
My lord of Cambridge
and my kind lord of Masham...

292
00:23:53,452 --> 00:23:55,851
and you, my gentle knight,
give me your thoughts.

293
00:23:55,951 --> 00:23:58,542
Think you not that
the powers we bear with us...

294
00:23:58,642 --> 00:24:01,329
will cut their passage
through the force of France?

295
00:24:01,429 --> 00:24:04,948
No doubt, my liege, if each man
do his best. I doubt not that.

296
00:24:05,048 --> 00:24:08,376
Never was monarch better feared
and loved than is your majesty.

297
00:24:08,476 --> 00:24:12,317
We therefore have great
cause of thankfulness.

298
00:24:12,417 --> 00:24:15,520
Uncle of Exeter, enlarge the
man committed yesterday...

299
00:24:15,620 --> 00:24:17,474
that railed against
our person.

300
00:24:17,574 --> 00:24:21,736
We consider it was excess of
wine that set him on,

301
00:24:21,836 --> 00:24:23,530
And on his more advice
we pardon him.

302
00:24:23,630 --> 00:24:25,964
That's mercy,
but too much security.

303
00:24:26,064 --> 00:24:31,025
Let him be punished, lest example breed
by his sufferance, more of such a kind.

304
00:24:31,125 --> 00:24:35,254
Oh, let us yet be merciful.

305
00:24:35,354 --> 00:24:38,617
So may your highness,
and yet punish too.

306
00:24:38,717 --> 00:24:41,052
Sir, you show great mercy
if you give him life...

307
00:24:41,152 --> 00:24:43,262
after the taste
of much correction.

308
00:24:43,362 --> 00:24:46,786
Alas, your too much love
and care of me...

309
00:24:46,886 --> 00:24:49,573
are heavy orisons
against this poor wretch.

310
00:24:49,673 --> 00:24:54,602
If little faults proceeding on
distemper shall not be winked at,

311
00:24:54,702 --> 00:25:00,368
how shall we stretch our eye
when capital crimes, chewed,

312
00:25:00,468 --> 00:25:03,816
swallowed and digested,
appear before us?

313
00:25:05,432 --> 00:25:07,608
We'll yet enlarge that man,

314
00:25:07,708 --> 00:25:10,491
though Cambridge,
Scroop and Grey,

315
00:25:10,591 --> 00:25:13,919
in their dear care
and tender preservation...

316
00:25:14,019 --> 00:25:17,762
of our person
would have him punished.

317
00:25:18,983 --> 00:25:21,951
And now to
our French causes.

318
00:25:22,956 --> 00:25:25,228
Who are the late commissioners?
I one, my lord.

319
00:25:25,328 --> 00:25:27,629
Your highness bade me
ask for it today. So did you me.

320
00:25:27,729 --> 00:25:30,385
- And I.
- Then, Richard Earl of cambridge, there is yours.

321
00:25:30,485 --> 00:25:32,851
There yours,
Lord Scroop of Masham,

322
00:25:32,951 --> 00:25:35,478
and sir knight, Grey of
Northumberland, this same is yours.

323
00:25:35,578 --> 00:25:36,723
Read them...

324
00:25:36,891 --> 00:25:38,201
and know...

325
00:25:39,326 --> 00:25:42,621
I know your worthiness.

326
00:25:44,740 --> 00:25:47,970
My Lord of Westmoreland,
uncle Exeter, we will aboard tonight.

327
00:25:52,940 --> 00:25:54,507
Why, how now, gentlemen

328
00:25:54,607 --> 00:25:58,094
what see you in those papers
that you lose so much complexion?

329
00:25:58,194 --> 00:26:01,554
I do confess my fault and do
submit me to your highness' mercy.

330
00:26:01,654 --> 00:26:05,398
- To which we all appeal.
- The mercy that was quick in us of late...

331
00:26:05,498 --> 00:26:07,896
by your own counsel
is suppressed and killed.

332
00:26:07,996 --> 00:26:12,413
You must not dare for shame
to talk of mercy!

333
00:26:12,513 --> 00:26:18,015
For your own reasons turn into your bosoms
as dogs upon their masters worrying you.

334
00:26:28,114 --> 00:26:33,492
See you, my princes and my noble
peers, these English monsters.

335
00:26:33,592 --> 00:26:35,927
What shall I say to thee,
Lord Scroop,

336
00:26:36,027 --> 00:26:39,291
thou cruel, ingrateful,

337
00:26:39,391 --> 00:26:43,231
savage and inhuman creature?

338
00:26:43,331 --> 00:26:45,552
Thou knave thou!

339
00:26:45,652 --> 00:26:49,017
Thou that didst bear the key of all my counsels,
that knewest the very bottom of my soul,

340
00:26:49,117 --> 00:26:50,983
that almost mightst have
coined me into gold,

341
00:26:51,083 --> 00:26:53,451
which thou have practiced
on me for thy use.

342
00:26:53,551 --> 00:26:56,013
May it be possible
that foreign hire...

343
00:26:56,113 --> 00:27:00,530
could out of thee extract one spark
of evil that might annoy my finger?

344
00:27:00,630 --> 00:27:02,354
'Tis so strange...

345
00:27:02,487 --> 00:27:06,649
that though the truth of it stand
off as gross as black and white,

346
00:27:06,749 --> 00:27:08,890
my eye will scarcely see it.

347
00:27:08,990 --> 00:27:13,984
So... constant and unspotted
didst thou seem...

348
00:27:14,084 --> 00:27:17,733
that this thy fall
hath left a kind of blot...

349
00:27:17,833 --> 00:27:20,923
to mark
the full-fraught man...

350
00:27:21,023 --> 00:27:25,192
and best indued
with some suspicion.

351
00:27:29,576 --> 00:27:31,428
I will weep for thee.

352
00:27:31,528 --> 00:27:37,471
For this revolt of thine, methinks,
is like another fall of man.

353
00:27:54,212 --> 00:27:58,782
I arrest thee of high treason by the
name of Richard Earl of Cambridge.

354
00:28:00,258 --> 00:28:04,795
I arrest thee of high treason by the name
of Thomas Grey, Knight of Northumberland.

355
00:28:06,498 --> 00:28:11,100
I arrest thee of high treason by the
name of Henry Lord Scroop of Masham.

356
00:28:15,489 --> 00:28:17,015
Hear your sentence.

357
00:28:18,080 --> 00:28:20,221
You have conspired
against our royal person,

358
00:28:20,321 --> 00:28:22,685
joined with an enemy
proclaimed and from his coffers...

359
00:28:22,785 --> 00:28:24,989
received the golden earnest
of our death wherein.

360
00:28:25,089 --> 00:28:27,228
You would have sold your king
to slaughter,

361
00:28:27,328 --> 00:28:29,435
his princes and his peers
to servitude,

362
00:28:29,535 --> 00:28:31,419
his subjects to oppression
and contempt...

363
00:28:31,519 --> 00:28:35,323
and his whole kingdom
into desolation!

364
00:28:37,053 --> 00:28:41,657
Get you therefore hence, poor
miserable wretches, to your death,

365
00:28:41,757 --> 00:28:45,497
the taste whereof God of his mercy
give you patience to endure...

366
00:28:45,597 --> 00:28:50,580
and true repentance
of all your dear offenses.

367
00:28:52,059 --> 00:28:53,203
Bear them hence.

368
00:29:00,762 --> 00:29:02,615
Now, Lords, for France,

369
00:29:02,715 --> 00:29:05,876
the enterprise whereof shall
be to you, as us, like glorious,

370
00:29:05,976 --> 00:29:10,577
since God so graciously hath brought to light
this dangerous treason lurking in our way.

371
00:29:10,677 --> 00:29:12,300
Cheerly to sea.

372
00:29:13,171 --> 00:29:14,958
The signs of war advance.

373
00:29:15,058 --> 00:29:19,755
No king of England
if not king of France.

374
00:30:01,331 --> 00:30:04,046
Prithee, honey-sweet husband,
let me bring thee to staines.

375
00:30:04,146 --> 00:30:09,195
No, for my manly heart
doth yearn.

376
00:30:09,295 --> 00:30:12,521
Bardolph, be blithe.

377
00:30:14,091 --> 00:30:17,575
Nym, rouse
thy vaunting veins.

378
00:30:17,675 --> 00:30:22,339
Boy, bristle
thy courage up.

379
00:30:22,598 --> 00:30:24,898
For Falstaff is dead,

380
00:30:24,998 --> 00:30:28,000
and we must yearn therefore.

381
00:30:28,100 --> 00:30:30,908
Would I were with him, wheresome'er
he is, either in heaven or in hell.

382
00:30:31,008 --> 00:30:32,285
Nay, sure,
he's not in hell.

383
00:30:32,385 --> 00:30:36,985
He's in Arthur's bosom, if ever
a man went to Arthur's bosom.

384
00:30:37,373 --> 00:30:41,810
He made a finer end and went away
an it had been any Christian child.

385
00:30:44,761 --> 00:30:47,605
He parted even
just between 12:00 and 1:00,

386
00:30:49,462 --> 00:30:51,827
even at the turning of the tide.

387
00:30:52,819 --> 00:30:55,663
For after I saw him
fumble with the sheets...

388
00:30:55,763 --> 00:31:00,743
and play with flowers and
smile upon his finger's ends,

389
00:31:01,613 --> 00:31:04,642
I knew there was
but one way.

390
00:31:07,177 --> 00:31:10,109
For his nose
was as sharp as a pen,

391
00:31:12,262 --> 00:31:15,194
and he babbled of green fields.

392
00:31:16,228 --> 00:31:18,240
"How now, Sir John," quoth I.

393
00:31:18,340 --> 00:31:20,638
"What, man?
Be of good cheer."

394
00:31:22,240 --> 00:31:26,263
So he cried out,
"God, God,

395
00:31:26,814 --> 00:31:28,372
God,"

396
00:31:30,330 --> 00:31:31,987
Three or four times.

397
00:31:35,735 --> 00:31:39,730
Now I, to comfort him, bid him
he should not think of God.

398
00:31:39,830 --> 00:31:43,371
I hoped there was no need to trouble himself
with any such thoughts yet.

399
00:31:47,024 --> 00:31:49,989
He bade me put
more clothes on his feet.

400
00:31:50,223 --> 00:31:54,408
I put my hand under the bed
and felt them,

401
00:31:57,194 --> 00:32:00,256
and they were as cold
as any stone.

402
00:32:02,310 --> 00:32:04,926
Then I felt to his knees,

403
00:32:06,373 --> 00:32:11,224
and so upward... and upward,

404
00:32:15,006 --> 00:32:16,412
and all was as...

405
00:32:18,332 --> 00:32:20,240
cold as any stone.

406
00:32:27,287 --> 00:32:30,385
They say he cried out for sack.
That he did.

407
00:32:30,485 --> 00:32:32,464
And of women.
No, that he did not.

408
00:32:32,564 --> 00:32:33,711
Yeah, that he did.

409
00:32:33,811 --> 00:32:36,878
He said they were...
devils incarnate.

410
00:32:36,978 --> 00:32:40,236
He could never abide carnation.
It was a color he never liked.

411
00:32:41,358 --> 00:32:43,593
He said once the devil
would have him about women.

412
00:32:43,693 --> 00:32:48,520
Well, he did in some sort...
handle women.

413
00:32:51,080 --> 00:32:54,178
But then he was rheumatic and
talked of the whore of Babylon.

414
00:32:54,278 --> 00:32:58,080
Do you not remember he saw a flea
stick upon Bardolph's nose?

415
00:32:58,180 --> 00:33:01,438
He said it was a black soul
burning in hell.

416
00:33:01,538 --> 00:33:04,252
Well, the fuel is gone
that maintained that fire.

417
00:33:04,352 --> 00:33:07,315
That's all the riches
I got in his service.

418
00:33:11,259 --> 00:33:12,567
Whall we shog?

419
00:33:13,913 --> 00:33:16,594
The king will be gone
from Southampton.

420
00:33:31,789 --> 00:33:33,097
Farewell, hostess.

421
00:33:35,403 --> 00:33:36,831
I cannot kiss.

422
00:33:37,705 --> 00:33:39,717
That's the humor of it.

423
00:33:39,817 --> 00:33:40,993
But...

424
00:33:47,012 --> 00:33:48,352
Adieu.

425
00:34:02,681 --> 00:34:05,461
Let housewifery appear.

426
00:34:05,816 --> 00:34:09,009
Keep close.

427
00:34:11,380 --> 00:34:12,721
I thee command.

428
00:34:17,264 --> 00:34:18,604
Farewell.

429
00:34:30,248 --> 00:34:31,556
Adieu.

430
00:34:38,626 --> 00:34:41,598
Follow, follow.

431
00:34:41,698 --> 00:34:45,275
For who is he whose chin is but
enriched with one appearing hair...

432
00:34:45,375 --> 00:34:49,208
that will not follow these
culled and choice-drawn cavaliers...

433
00:34:49,308 --> 00:34:51,160
to France?

434
00:35:11,917 --> 00:35:16,997
Thus comes the English...
with full power upon us,

435
00:35:18,889 --> 00:35:23,871
and more than carefully it us concerns
to answer royally in our defenses.

436
00:35:25,605 --> 00:35:28,384
Therefore,
the dukes of Berri...

437
00:35:28,484 --> 00:35:29,943
and of Bretagne,

438
00:35:30,530 --> 00:35:35,032
of Brabant and of Orleans
shall make forth.

439
00:35:35,518 --> 00:35:37,243
And you, prince Dauphin...

440
00:35:37,343 --> 00:35:38,906
My most redoubted father,

441
00:35:39,006 --> 00:35:42,935
it is most meet we arm us
against the foe.

442
00:35:43,035 --> 00:35:46,260
For peace itself
should not so dull a kingdom,

443
00:35:46,360 --> 00:35:48,914
but the defenses, musters,
preparations should be maintained,

444
00:35:49,014 --> 00:35:51,922
assembled and collected,
as were a war in expectation.

445
00:35:52,022 --> 00:35:55,087
Therefore, I say 'tis meet
we all go forth to view...

446
00:35:55,187 --> 00:35:57,774
the sick and feeble
parts of France.

447
00:35:57,874 --> 00:36:00,875
And let us do it
with no show of fear!

448
00:36:00,975 --> 00:36:03,817
No, with no more than if we heard
that England were busied with,

449
00:36:03,917 --> 00:36:06,919
uh, a Whitsun morris dance.

450
00:36:07,019 --> 00:36:10,725
For, my good liege, she is so idly
kinged by a vain, giddy, shallow,

451
00:36:10,825 --> 00:36:13,251
humorous youth,
that fear attends her not.

452
00:36:13,351 --> 00:36:14,659
O peace, prince dauphin.

453
00:36:14,759 --> 00:36:17,312
You're too much mistaken
in this king.

454
00:36:17,412 --> 00:36:20,542
Question, your grace,
the late ambassadors.

455
00:36:20,642 --> 00:36:23,676
With what great state
he heard their embassy,

456
00:36:23,776 --> 00:36:26,682
how well supplied
with noble counselors,

457
00:36:26,782 --> 00:36:31,256
how modest in exception
and withal how terrible...

458
00:36:31,356 --> 00:36:34,100
in constant resolution.

459
00:36:38,422 --> 00:36:40,306
Well, 'tis not so,
my lord high constable.

460
00:36:40,406 --> 00:36:43,376
Though we think it so,
'tis no matter.

461
00:36:43,476 --> 00:36:46,830
In matters of defense, 'tis best to weigh
the enemy more mighty than he seems.

462
00:36:46,930 --> 00:36:50,220
Think we king Harry strong.

463
00:36:52,301 --> 00:36:56,640
And, princes, look you
strongly armed to meet him.

464
00:36:56,906 --> 00:36:59,750
For he is bred
out of that bloody strain...

465
00:36:59,850 --> 00:37:03,903
that haunted us
in our familiar paths.

466
00:37:04,390 --> 00:37:06,722
Witness our too-much
memorable shame...

467
00:37:06,822 --> 00:37:11,192
when cressy battle
fatally was struck...

468
00:37:12,065 --> 00:37:15,227
and all our princes captived...

469
00:37:15,327 --> 00:37:18,454
by the hand
of that black name,

470
00:37:18,747 --> 00:37:19,990
Edward,

471
00:37:20,443 --> 00:37:23,855
black prince of Wales.

472
00:37:26,423 --> 00:37:31,314
This is a stem
of that victorious stalk.

473
00:37:31,414 --> 00:37:34,607
And let us fear
the native mightiness...

474
00:37:34,707 --> 00:37:37,006
and fate of him.

475
00:37:57,123 --> 00:38:01,341
Ambassadors from Harry, king of England,
do crave admittance to your majesty.

476
00:38:02,049 --> 00:38:04,567
Go and bring them.

477
00:38:07,549 --> 00:38:11,288
You see, this chase
is hotly followed, friends.

478
00:38:17,399 --> 00:38:21,202
Good my sovereign,
take up the English short,

479
00:38:21,302 --> 00:38:25,105
and let them know of what a
monarchy you are the head.

480
00:38:26,130 --> 00:38:31,362
Self-love, my liege, is not so vile
a sin as self-neglecting.

481
00:38:46,788 --> 00:38:48,643
From our brother England?

482
00:38:48,743 --> 00:38:53,479
From him, and thus
he greets your majesty.

